          "heading": "4. Logical Flaws & Observations",
          "content_markdown": "- **Party presentation at emergency-docket altitude.** The most striking structural feature of *Cook* is what the majority *doesn't* decide. The Government did not challenge the constitutionality of \u00a7 242's removal restriction. The majority accepts that concession and resolves the case on statutory grounds. Barrett's dissent argues the majority still goes too broadly (naming the historical-tradition carveout in Part III-A(2) despite the constitutional question being waived); Alito's dissent goes further, arguing the majority should not have opined on any issue beyond the two the D.C. Circuit resolved (due process + \"cause\" scope). This tension \u2014 between judicial restraint and interim-docket transparency \u2014 is the same tension Barrett named in *Mirabelli v. Bonta*, 607 U.S. 492 (2026): \"lock-in risk of saying too much against the transparency cost of saying too little.\" *Cook* comes down closer to the \"saying enough to be useful\" side, and the meta-honesty note is that reasonable minds can disagree.\n\n- **The \"cause\" definition the Court leaves open.** The majority \"need not fully demarcate the contours of 'cause' today.\" That's *In re Nichols*-style deferential language, but it means the substantive standard remains to be fleshed out on remand. Lower courts now have to apply a \"substantial threshold\" reflecting the Federal Reserve's role \u2014 likely a two-step analysis: (a) seriousness of misconduct; (b) nexus to professional duties. Whether *Cook*'s alleged pre-office mortgage fraud clears that bar is the merits question the majority carefully does *not* resolve.\n\n- **Thomas's Article II theory as inverse counterpoint.** Thomas's dissent is the pure Article II unitary-executive position: removal power is inherent in the vesting clause; Congress cannot limit it; the statute is unconstitutional. The dissent's historical work is thorough but faces the problem the majority names: the historical tradition of central bank independence *predates* the Constitution (Bank of North America 1781) and was reaffirmed by the same Founders who ratified Article II. This is one of the few areas where founding-era practice cuts *against* a strong unitary-executive reading, and Thomas's response \u2014 that the Federal Reserve isn't really analogous to the First/Second Banks \u2014 is precisely the fact-intensive line the majority declines to draw at this stage.\n\n- **The equitable-relief holding is quietly load-bearing.** *In re Sawyer* and *White v. Berry* had been read broadly to foreclose equitable relief in officer-removal cases. *Cook* clarifies that these cases addressed *final* equitable relief where legal remedies (mandamus, quo warranto, backpay) were adequate \u2014 they do not foreclose *interim* protection of officers pending litigation. This preserves preliminary-injunction practice for wrongfully-removed officers, which had been in real doubt after *Wilcox* and *Boyle* stay orders.\n\n- **The stale-hash procedural detail worth naming.** The dispute over notice-and-hearing carries a substantive undercurrent: the majority (Part III-B) rejects the Government's argument that Trump's social-media post (\"Cook must resign, now!!!\") constituted adequate notice. What \"will not do\" is a post that \"did not suggest that a response from Cook would be appropriate, nor did it even provide a clear account of the charge made against her.\" The rule that emerges: notice must include (i) some explanation of evidence at issue, (ii) some avenue for response, (iii) a deadline. *Mullane v. Central Hanover Bank & Trust Co.*, 339 U.S. 306, 314\u2013315 (1950) is invoked by analogy. This is the shape of due process bleeding into statutory-notice doctrine."
