          "heading": "5. Follow-ups for Mr. C",
          "content_markdown": "- **Doctrinal-scaffold angle (for JR's returning-paralegal register):** The core structural move in *Cook* is a **presumption + backdrop-rebuttal** pattern. Congress enacts fixed-term + for-cause \u2192 *presumed* to legislate against the common-law backdrop (*Comcast*, *Jam*) \u2192 common-law backdrop is *Reagan/Shurtleff*'s notice-and-hearing rule \u2192 therefore statute implicitly requires notice-and-hearing. This is the same shape as the FIAFEA presumption-of-review rebuttal analysis in [[24-1990|Jacobson v. United States]] and the \"true nature\" doctrine in [[24-2242|Erdemir v. ITC]] \u2014 Congress presumed to write against a settled backdrop, backdrop displaced only by clear-and-convincing showing to the contrary. **Worth naming as a discrete category:** \"backdrop rebuttable presumptions\" as a distinct interpretive doctrine.\n\n- **Weight-of-words angle:** \"For cause\" carries centuries of common-law weight \u2014 it is not a phrase Congress uses lightly. The majority's move is to make that weight legible: \"Congress enacted this statute 'against the backdrop of the common law,' such that we must look to the common law to decipher what 'cause' (a term of art) requires.\" Two words with statutory weight; two centuries of case law loaded into them. This is the same discipline as reading \"true nature\" (Erdemir), \"arbitrary and capricious\" (APA), or \"reasonable\" (contract law) \u2014 none of which mean what plain-English reading would suggest. **The lesson worth naming:** statutory terms with common-law pedigrees are never plain-English; they carry their history.\n\n- **Structural analogy (rigid statutes, flexible analysis):** *Cook* is a beautiful example of the rigid-in-statutes-but-flexible-in-analysis pattern you named in your legal-background reflection. The statutory language is fixed (\"for cause\"), but its application to the Federal Reserve's unique historical role is deeply flexible \u2014 the \"substantial threshold\" the Court identifies depends on the \"nature of the service to be performed\" and \"duties of the office.\" Same phrase, different bite in different institutional contexts. Compare to the Federal Circuit's willingness to distinguish *Fisher* in [[24-1990|Jacobson]] based on whether jurisdiction blends with merits \u2014 same doctrinal source, differently binding depending on structural shape.\n\n- **The historical-tradition safe harbor as a new (or newly-explicit) doctrine.** *Slaughter* announces a general rule (Article II requires at-will removal of principal executive officers) but preserves specific historical-tradition carveouts (Federal Reserve; non-Article III courts reserved). *Cook* activates the Federal Reserve carveout. This is a doctrinal shape worth naming because it will recur: \"general rule + historical-tradition carveout\" is how the Court is going to handle other structural-Constitution questions where founding-era practice cuts against modern theory. Watch for it in future terms.\n\n- **Cross-stitch with prior corpus.** *Cook* + *Slaughter* together sit at the top of the removal-law doctrinal tree; every future case in this space (agency independence, civil service, MSPB, adjudicative bodies) will trace back here. Pair with *Free Enterprise Fund*, *Seila Law*, *Collins v. Yellen*, *Wilcox*, and *Boyle* to see the compound arc: from *Humphrey's Executor* (1935) \u2192 *Wiener* (1958) \u2192 *Free Enterprise Fund* (2010) \u2192 *Seila Law* (2020) \u2192 *Slaughter* + *Cook* (2026). **Recommend an SR Sharpens pass on this arc as a foundational doctrinal-map exercise** \u2014 it teaches Article II removal law through evolution, which is exactly how doctrine is best learned from ground zero.\n\n- **Field Clerk paired 2026-07-11:** [[25A312|Field Clerk Draft \u2014 25A312 (Trump v. Cook)]] at `Terminal/Central Hub/research/data/legal/field-clerks/25A312.md`. Isolates four carry-forward doctrines: (i) backdrop rebuttable presumption (**promoted to named war-chest doctrine** \u2014 third data point after Jacobson + Erdemir); (ii) historical-tradition safe harbor; (iii) equity protects de facto officer pending litigation; (iv) notice adequacy three-part rule.\n\n- **Watch thread:** whether the Sixth Circuit or Fifth Circuit tries to extend *Cook*'s historical-tradition carveout to other agencies (FDIC, OCC, SEC via *Free Enterprise Fund* residuum). Also watch: what happens on remand as the D.C. District Court applies the \"substantial threshold\" cause standard to Cook's alleged pre-office conduct."
