          "heading": "Main Opinion Summary",
          "content_markdown": "Chief Justice Roberts, writing for a five-Justice majority (joined by Sotomayor, Kagan, Kavanaugh, and Jackson), denies the President's application for a stay of the D.C. District Court's preliminary injunction restoring Governor Lisa Cook to her position on the Federal Reserve Board. In August 2025, President Trump purported to fire Cook \u2014 the first Federal Reserve Governor fired in the central bank's 111-year history \u2014 for alleged mortgage fraud committed shortly before she assumed office. The District Court enjoined the removal on due process and \"for cause\" statutory grounds; the D.C. Circuit refused a stay. **The Court holds:** (1) The Government has not shown likelihood of success on the merits. Federal Reserve Act \u00a7 242's \"for cause\" language is judicially reviewable (rejecting the Government's textual-commitment argument); \"cause\" is a common-law term of art requiring a substantial threshold reflecting the Federal Reserve's unique historical role; the President's determination is not immune from review. (2) On the narrowest available ground, the President failed to afford Cook the notice-and-opportunity-to-respond that fixed-term + for-cause statutes implicitly require under the *Reagan/Shurtleff* rule. Trump's social-media post did not constitute constitutionally adequate notice. (3) Federal courts have equitable authority to grant interim reinstatement pending merits litigation \u2014 *In re Sawyer* and *White v. Berry* addressed final equitable relief where legal remedies were adequate, not interim protection of *de facto* officers. (4) The Federal Reserve's statutory removal restriction is constitutional under Article II because the Federal Reserve follows in the \"distinct historical tradition\" of the First and Second Banks of the United States \u2014 an independence \"sanctioned by history\" that the Framers themselves guaranteed against Presidential control. Concurring opinions by Kavanaugh (emphasizing the risk of leaving the Federal Reserve's status open post-*Slaughter*) and Jackson (relying primarily on equitable factors). Dissents by Thomas (Article II forecloses any removal restriction on principal officers; statute is unconstitutional; equity cannot interfere with removal), Alito joined by Gorsuch (majority reached too many issues on an underdeveloped record), and Barrett (concurring in some critiques of scope; also arguing the injunction is broader than the majority acknowledges). **Application for stay DENIED.** Decided companion to [[trump_v_slaughter|Trump v. Slaughter]] the same day."
